{{for|the 2015 Ladies edition|2015 Ladies Tour of Qatar}}

The '''2015 Tour of Qatar''' was the 14th edition of the [[Tour of Qatar]] cycling stage race. It was organised by the [[Amaury Sport Organisation]] (ASO), the organisers of the [[Tour de France]]. The race was rated as a [[2.HC]] event, the second highest rating an event can receive, and was part of the [[2015 UCI Asia Tour]].

The 2015 race consisted of six stages. It started in [[Dukhan]] on 8 February 2015 and finished on 13 February in [[Doha]], the capital city of [[Qatar]]. The Tour of Qatar puts unusual demands on riders: it has no significant climbs, but almost every stage is affected by strong [[crosswind]]s. These conditions make the race ideal preparation for the [[Classic_cycle_races#Spring_classics|spring classics]] season, so many prominent classics riders were present. The flat stages, suitable for sprinters, and [[individual time trial]] meant that specialists in these disciplines also chose to ride in Qatar.

The race was won by [[Netherlands|Dutch]] rider [[Niki Terpstra]] of {{ct|OPQ|2015}}. It was the second successive year that Terpstra won the race after his victory in [[2014 Tour of Qatar|2014]] and the fourth successive victory for {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}}. It was the eighth victory for the team in Qatar. Terpstra took the lead of the race with victory in the third stage of the race, the individual time trial, and held the lead of the race to the finish. [[Maciej Bodnar]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}) took second place, six seconds behind Terpstra; [[Alexander Kristoff]] won stages 2, 4 and 5 on the way to finishing third, nine seconds off the overall lead.

In the race's other classifications, Kristoff won the silver jersey of the points classification, thanks to his three stage wins. [[Peter Sagan]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}) was the winner of the pearl white jersey of the young riders classification as he was the highest placed rider born after 1 January 1990. The team classification was won by {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}}.

== Preview ==

[[File:Tom Boonen MS 2012 (cropped).jpg|160px|thumbnail|right|Tom Boonen, four times the overall victor at the Tour of Qatar]]
The Tour of Qatar is one of the early races in the season, coming in the middle of three races in the Middle East (alongside the [[2015 Dubai Tour|Dubai Tour]] and the [[2015 Tour of Oman|Tour of Oman]]) that see high levels of participation from the top European teams.<ref name=cyclingnews-preview>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Tour of Qatar: Etixx-QuickStep look to continue domination|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-qatar-2015/preview|website=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> The race is particularly popular as a preparation race for riders aiming for the [[Classic_cycle_races#Spring_classics|spring classics]].<ref name=skysports-preview>{{cite web|last1=Westby|first1=Matt|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 preview: Sir Bradley Wiggins, Tom Boonen and Niki Terpstra among favourites for victory|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cycling/news/12040/9703278/tour-of-qatar-2015-preview-sir-bradley-wiggins-tom-boonen-and-niki-terpstra-among-favourites-for-victory|website=[[Skysports.com]]|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> The significant challenge in the Tour of Qatar is the strong winds across the desert, which frequently cause the peloton to split into echelons. As well as attracting the top classics riders, the flat nature of the course means many stages can be won by sprinters; the [[individual time trial]] also attracts many of the time trial specialists, who have a chance of overall victory.<ref name=cyclingnews-preview/>

{{ct|OPQ|2015}} had dominated the race since it began. This included winning the last three editions (with [[Tom Boonen]], [[Mark Cavendish]] and [[Niki Terpstra]]).<ref name=cyclingnews-preview/><ref name=pcs-history>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - General Classification|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015-editions|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> Boonen had won the overall race on four previous occasions, as well as winning 22 stages.<ref name=cyclingstages>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar: All Winners|url=http://www.cyclingstage.com/tour-of-qatar-2015/winners-qatar/|website=CyclingStages.com|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref> Boonen and Terpstra were both among the favourites for the overall victory, along with world time-trial champion [[Bradley Wiggins]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}).<ref>{{cite web|title=Bradley Wiggins is main Tour of Qatar threat, says Tom Boonen|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/bradley-wiggins-main-tour-qatar-threat-says-tom-boonen-156488|website=Cycling Weekly|accessdate=12 February 2015}}</ref>

[[Marcel Kittel]] ({{ct|GIA|2015}}) was the most prominent sprinter to travel to Qatar, alongside [[Peter Sagan]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}), [[Alexander Kristoff]] ({{ct|KAT|2015}}), and several others.<ref name=cyclingnews-preview/>

== Teams ==

18 teams have been selected to take part in the event, including 13 [[UCI WorldTeam]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Teams|url=http://www.letour.fr/tour-of-qatar/2015/us/teams.html|website=letour.com|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Each team was permitted to include between five and eight riders.<ref name=letour-rules/> 15 teams had the full allowance of eight riders; 3 teams had seven-man teams. The race therefore began with 141 riders.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - General Classification|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015-startlist|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref> 9 of these withdrew during the course of the event; 132 finished the final stage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - General Classification|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015-result|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=5 April 2015}}</ref>

