=== Stage 1 ===

[[File:Tour du Qatar 2015 (A1).jpg|thumbnail|right|Stage 1 route]]

The race began with a {{convert|136|km|0|abbr=on}} route from [[Dukhan]] in the west of Qatar to the Sealine Beach Resort, [[Mesaieed]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - Stage 1|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015_Stage_1_Sealine_Beach-stages|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> The route was flat and, as normal in the Tour of Qatar, the principal difficulty was caused by [[crosswind]]s.<ref name=cyclingnews-s1-results>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015: Stage 1 Results|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-qatar-2015/stage-1/results|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Jos<U+00E9> Joaqu<U+00ED>n Rojas TDF 2013 (Cropping).jpg|160px|thumbnail|left|[[Jos<U+00E9> Joaqu<U+00ED>n Rojas]] (pictured here in 2013) won stage 1]]The initial [[Glossary_of_cycling#breakaway|breakaway]] was formed early in the race by [[Luca Sterbini]] ({{ct|CSF|2015}}) and [[Jarl Salomein]] ({{ct|TSV|2015}}). They built a lead that reached seven minutes by the half-way point. Midway through the stage, a change in direction meant the peloton was now racing in crosswinds, and {{ct|OPQ|2015}} along with {{ct|TFR|2015}} attacked. They formed [[Glossary_of_cycling#echelon|echelons]] and split the peloton. Riders such as [[Bradley Wiggins]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}), [[Nacer Bouhanni]] ({{ct|COF|2015}}) and [[Alejandro Valverde]] ({{ct|MOV|2015}}) were left adrift from the front group, but another turn into a headwind meant the groups could come back together.<ref name="cyclingnews-s1-results"/>

Shortly before the second intermediate sprint, [[Tom Boonen]] ({{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}}) and [[Peter Sagan]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}) were involved in a crash, but were both able to remount and rejoin the peloton.<ref name=cyclingnews-s1-boonencrash>{{cite web|title=Boonen and Sagan crash mid-race in Tour of Qatar opener|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/boonen-and-sagan-crash-mid-race-in-tour-of-qatar-opener|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> After [[Nikias Arndt]] ({{ct|GIA|2015}}) won that sprint, [[Greg Van Avermaet]] made a short-lived attack before a more determined effort from [[Lars Boom]] and [[Lieuwe Westra]] (both {{ct|AST|2015}}) and [[Matti Breschel]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}).<ref name="cyclingnews-s1-results"/> Though they achieved a lead of nearly a minute, the attack was ultimately unsuccessful, due to crosswinds and a combination of {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}}, {{ct|TFR|2015|nolink=yes}} and {{ct|TNE|2015}} riding at a high tempo.<ref name="cyclingnews-s1-results"/><ref name=velonews-s1>{{cite web|title=Jose Joaquin Rojas wins opener at 2015 Tour of Qatar|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/02/news/jose-joaquin-rojas-wins-opener-2015-tour-qatar_360361|website=Velonews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

In the final {{convert|10|km|0|abbr=on}}, the peloton split again. The main field was reduced to 51 riders, with [[Marcel Kittel]] ({{ct|GIA|2015|nolink=yes}}), Wiggins, [[Edvald Boasson Hagen]] ({{ct|MTN|2015}}), [[Luca Paolini]] ({{ct|KAT|2015}}) and [[Filippo Pozzato]] ({{ct|LAM|2015}}) among the notable riders to lose time.<ref name="cyclingnews-s1-results"/><ref name=pcs-s1-result>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - Stage 1|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015_Stage_1_Sealine_Beach|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

In the final kilometre, [[Jos<U+00E9> Joaqu<U+00ED>n Rojas]] ({{ct|MOV|2015|nolink=yes}}) attached himself to the back of the {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}} leadout train. He opened his sprint with {{Convert|300|m|4 = -2|abbr = on}} remaining, taking other riders by surprise, and was able to hold them off and take the victory.<ref name=cyclingtips-s1>{{cite web|last1=de Neef|first1=Matt|title=Daily News Digest|url=http://cyclingtips.com.au/2015/02/daily-news-digest-11/|website=Cyclingtips.com.au|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> This was Rojas' first victory since the [[2014 Vuelta a Castilla y Le<U+00F3>n]].<ref name=cyclingweekly-s1>{{cite web|last1=Wynn|first1=Nigel|title=Jose Joaquin Rojas wins Tour of Qatar stage one as Wiggins loses time|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/jose-joaquin-rojas-wins-tour-qatar-stage-one-156524|website=Cycling Weekly|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

Boonen finished second in the sprint, with [[Arnaud D<U+00E9>mare]] ({{ct|FDJ|2015}}) third.<ref name="cyclingnews-s1-results"/>

