=== Stage 2 ===

[[File:Tour du Qatar 2015 (A2).jpg|thumbnail|right|Stage 2 route]]

The second stage took the riders {{convert|187.5|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Al Wakra]], south of [[Doha]], to [[Al Khor]] Corniche.<ref name=pcs-s2-profile>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - Stage 2|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015_Stage_2_Al_Khor_Corniche-profiles|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

Early in the stage, {{ct|OPQ|2015}} launched an attack, quickly splitting the pack in crosswinds to create a lead group of 30 riders.<ref name=cyclingnews-s2-warfare>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Etixx-QuickStep launch desert warfare in Qatar but Kristoff wins battle|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/etixx-quickstep-launch-desert-warfare-in-qatar-but-kristoff-wins-battle|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> Riders left behind included the race leader, [[Jos<U+00E9> Joaqu<U+00ED>n Rojas]] ({{ct|MOV|2015}}), [[Bradley Wiggins]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}), [[Marcel Kittel]] ({{ct|GIA|2015}}) and [[Lars Boom]] ({{ct|AST|2015}}). The lead group, however, failed to establish a lead of more than half a minute and work from {{ct|BMC|2015}} and {{ct|MTN|2015}} brought the field back together after {{convert|60|km|0|abbr=on}}, when the wind changed to a tailwind.<ref name=cyclingnews-s1-result>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Kristoff wins stage 2 at the Tour of Qatar|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-qatar-2015/stage-2/results|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=velonews-s2-result>{{cite web|title=Kristoff rides into Tour of Qatar lead with stage 2 win|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/02/news/road/kristoff-rides-tour-qatar-lead-stage-2-win_360390|website=VeloNews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

At this point a five-man breakaway formed, including [[Michael M<U+00F8>rk<U+00F8>v]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}), [[Greg Van Avermaet]] ({{ct|BMC|2015|nolink=yes}}), [[Johann Van Zyl]] ({{ct|MTN|2015|nolink=yes}}), [[Jelle Wallays]] ({{ct|TSV|2015}}), and [[Mathew Hayman]] ({{ct|OGE|2015}}), establishing a lead of nearly four minutes.<ref name=velonews-s2-result/>

[[File:Alexander Kristoff.JPG|160px|thumbnail|left|[[Alexander Kristoff]] (pictured here in 2009) won stages 2, 4 and 5]] At the next change of direction, {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}} again attacked in the crosswinds. The breakaway was caught after {{convert|124|km|0|abbr=on}}, with the peloton again splitting. Wiggins, Kittel and [[Fabian Cancellara]] ({{ct|TFR|2015}}) had all been dropped. Soon afterwards, further attacks from {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}} removed Rojas and [[Arnaud D<U+00E9>mare]] ({{ct|FDJ|2015}}) from the leading group.<ref name=cyclingnews-s1-result/> Tom Boonen won the second intermediate sprint, earning three bonus seconds.<ref name=cyclingnews-s2-warfare/>

With {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=on}} remaining, the leading group was reduced to 15 riders.<ref name=cyclingnews-s2-warfare/> In the final kilometre, [[Andrea Guardini]] and [[Niki Terpstra]] had formed a small gap, but [[Alexander Kristoff]] bridged up to the pair and launched his sprint with {{convert|500|m|0|abbr=on}} remaining. Kristoff was able to win the stage ahead of Guardini, with Van Avermaet in third.<ref name=cyclingnews-s1-result/>

Due to the 10-second time bonus for winning the stage, Kristoff took over the overall lead of the race, one second ahead of Boonen, who moved into the lead of the points competition. Several riders who had been contenders for the overall victory, including Wiggins and Cancellara, finished over nine minutes behind Kristoff, eliminating them from contention for overall victory.<ref name=cyclingnews-s1-result/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Cancellara: Tour of Qatar is a special race|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/cancellara-tour-of-qatar-is-a-special-race|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref>

