=== Stage 4 ===

[[File:Tour du Qatar 2015 (A4).jpg|thumbnail|right|Stage 4 route]]

The fourth stage of the race was a {{convert|165.5|km|0|abbr=on}} route from [[Al Thakhira]] to the city of [[Mesaieed#Industrial_city|Mesaieed]].<ref name=pcs-s4-route>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - Stage 4|url=www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015_Stage_4_Mesaieed-profiles|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> With the wind generally coming from the south, the riders were riding into a headwind most of the day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.com/tour-of-qatar/2015/us/stage-4/news/flm/kristoff-doubles-in-mesaieed.html|website=letour.com|publisher=Amaury Sports Organisation|accessdate=11 February 2015|title=Kristoff doubles in Mesaieed}}</ref>

Due to the strong winds, the stage started 40 minutes before the scheduled time, as the race organisers were worried about the possibility of sandstorms and of slow racing leading to a late finish. Despite the headwind, three riders formed a breakaway. They were [[Jaco Venter]] ({{ct|MTN|2015}}), [[Dimitry Gruzdev]] ({{ct|AST|2015}}), and [[Jarl Salomein]] ({{ct|TSV|2015}}). The three riders built a lead that reached nearly four minutes.<ref name=velonews-s4-report>{{cite web|title=Kristoff grabs another Qatar stage win, Terpstra stays in front|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/02/news/road/kristoff-grabs-another-qatar-stage-win-terpstra-stays-front_360629|website=Velonews|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=cyclingnews-s4-result>{{cite web|last1=Farrand|first1=Stephen|title=Kristoff strikes again in Mesaieed|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-qatar-2015/stage-4/results|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>

{{ct|OPQ|2015}}, riding for race leader Niki Terpstra,  controlled the breakaway through most of the day. They were supported towards the end of the race by {{ct|FDJ|2015}}.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-result/> Unlike the earlier road stages, the lack of crosswinds meant that there were no echelons or significant splits in the peloton.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-kristoff>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Kristoff enjoys best ever start to a season in Tour of Qatar|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/kristoff-enjoys-best-ever-start-to-a-season-in-tour-of-qatar|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> The breakaway was caught with {{convert|19|km|0|abbr=on}} remaining.<ref name=velonews-s4-report/>

[[File:Peter Sagan - UPCC 2013.jpg|thumbnail|160px|left|[[Peter Sagan]] (pictured here in 2013) was second in two stages and won the youth classification]]In the final kilometres of the stage, several teams tried to ride at the front, including {{Ct|MTN|2015|nolink=yes}}, {{ct|MOV|2015}}, {{ct|FDJ|2015|nolink=yes}}, {{ct|TTS|2015}} and {{ct|OGE|2015}}.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-result/><ref name=cyclingnews-s4-kristoff/> The strong pace caused several riders to crash, including [[Lars Boom]] ({{ct|AST|2015}}), [[Theo Bos]] ({{ct|MTN|2015|nolink=yes}}) and [[Bradley Wiggins]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}). All were unhurt and able to finish the stage.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-result/>

Despite the presence of [[Marcel Kittel]], the team's principal sprinter, {{ct|GIA|2015}} were riding in support of [[Nikias Arndt]]. Kittel took a turn in his lead-out train; since he was in poor form following a period of illness, he had requested the team support Arndt instead.<ref name=velonews-s4-kittel>{{cite web|last1=Brown|first1=Gregor|title=Kittel without sprint kick|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/02/news/kittel-without-sprint-kick_360635|website=Velonews.com|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>

In the final kilometre, the Katusha team moved to the front before Kristoff again started his sprint early; again, the other sprinters were unable to catch him and he crossed the finish line first.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-result/> He was only slightly ahead of [[Peter Sagan]] ({{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=yes}}), who was so close at the finish line that Kristoff was unsure whether he had won.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-kristoff/> Arndt was third after {{ct|GIA|2015|nolink=yes}} had done excellent work in the last kilometre.<ref name=cw-s4>{{cite web|last1=Stephen|first1=Puddicombe|title=Alexander Kristoff wins Tour of Qatar stage four|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/alexander-kristoff-wins-stage-four-tour-of-qatar-157022|website=Cycling Weekly|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>

There was a small split in the peloton at the end of the race. Several riders lost five seconds, including Terpstra, [[Ian Stannard]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}), [[Luke Rowe]] ({{ct|SKY|2015|nolink=yes}}), [[Greg Van Avermaet]] ({{ct|BMC|2015}}) and [[Tom Boonen]] ({{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}}). Kristoff moved up into fifth place in the overall standings thanks to this split and the time bonus for winning the stage. He also took over leadership of the silver jersey of the points classification. Terpstra retained his overall lead, while Rowe remained the leader of the young riders classification.<ref name=cyclingnews-s4-result/>

