=== Stage 5 ===

[[File:Tour du Qatar 2015 (A5).jpg|thumbnail|right|Stage 5 route]]

Stage 5 was a {{convert|153|km|0|abbr=on}} route starting at [[Al Zubarah Fort]]. The riders first travelled east towards [[Al Ghuwariyah]], before returning to Al Zubarah. The route then took them north-east along the coast, before finishing with two laps of a circuit in [[Madinat ash Shamal]].<ref name=pcs-s5-profile>{{cite web|title=Tour of Qatar 2015 - Stage 5|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tour_of_Qatar_2015_Stage_5_Madinat_ash_Shamal-profiles|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>

{{ct|OPQ|2015}} once again attacked early in the stage, breaking the peloton into echelons in the opening kilometres. [[Maciej Bodnar]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}), in second place overnight, was among the riders who failed to make the lead group. The gap between the groups never extended much beyond half a minute and, after around {{convert|60|km|0|abbr=on}} of racing, Bodnar's group was able to rejoin the lead group and the racing, which had been frenetic until that point, calmed down.<ref name=cyclingnews-s5-result>{{cite web|last1=Farrand|first1=Stephen|title=Kristoff takes his third sprint victory|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tour-of-qatar-2015/stage-5/results|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=velonews-s5-result>{{cite web|title=Kristoff takes win number three at Tour of Qatar|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/02/news/road/kristoff-takes-win-no-3-tour-qatar_360699|website=VeloNews|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>

[[File:Zubara Fort.jpg|180x180px|thumbnail|left|[[Al Zubarah Fort]]]] At that point a breakaway formed, made up of [[Ben Hermans]] ({{ct|BMC|2015}}), [[Marco Haller (cyclist)|Marco Haller]] ({{ct|KAT|2015}}), [[Jelle Wallays]] ({{ct|TSV|2015}}), [[Dmitriy Gruzdev]] ({{ct|AST|2015}}) and [[Mathew Hayman]] ({{ct|OGE|2015}}). The five riders at one point had a lead of over two and a half minutes.<ref name=cyclingtips-s5>{{cite web|title=Niki Terpstra keeps lead in Qatar despite Tinkoff-Saxo pressure|url=http://cyclingtips.com.au/2015/02/daily-news-digest-15/|website=Cyclingtips.com.au|accessdate=13 February 2015|first1=Matt|last1=de Neef}}</ref> Hayman won both intermediate sprints and at one point was virtual leader of the race, before the peloton behind took up the chase in earnest. The breakaway was caught with {{convert|13|km|0|abbr=on}} remaining.<ref name=cyclingnews-s5-result/><ref name=velonews-s5-result/>

In the final six kilometres, {{ct|KAT|2015|nolink=yes}} and {{ct|BMC|2015|nolink=yes}} attacked and forced another split in the peloton. [[Tom Boonen]] was among two {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}} riders in the 10-man front group, but [[Niki Terpstra]], the race leader, was not. [[Alexander Kristoff]] ({{ct|KAT|2015|nolink=yes}}) and Maciej Bodnar were in the lead group, which built a lead of 15 seconds. Terpstra would have lost the race lead, but {{ct|OPQ|2015|nolink=yes}} were able to bring the groups back together.<ref name=velonews-s5-result/><ref name=cyclingweekly-s5>{{cite web|last1=Nick|first1=Bull|title=Niki Terpstra keeps lead in Qatar despite Tinkoff-Saxo pressure|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/niki-terpstra-keeps-lead-qatar-despite-tinkoff-saxo-pressure-157304|website=Cycling Weekly|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> After the race, it was revealed that the three {{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=yes}} riders in the leading group were not aware that Terpstra had been dropped and, with team radios banned, [[Directeur sportif|''directeur sportif'']] [[Bjarne Riis]] was not able to inform them.<ref name=cyclingweekly-s5/><ref name=cyclingnews-s5-kristoff>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/kristoff-realistic-about-chances-of-winning-tour-of-qatar|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/kristoff-realistic-about-chances-of-winning-tour-of-qatar|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>

As they approached the finishing line, Kristoff again opened his sprint early and was able to hold off the rest of the field for his third stage victory of the race. [[Peter Sagan]] ({{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=yes}}) finished second and [[Nikias Arndt]], again sprinting for {{ct|GIA|2015}} in place of [[Marcel Kittel]], finished third. Sagan therefore moved into first place in the young riders competition, overtaking [[Luke Rowe]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}).<ref name=cyclingnews-s5-result/>

Thanks to the time bonus on the finish line, Kristoff was now in third place overall, just 11 seconds behind Terpstra. This meant that Kristoff could win the overall victory in the race if he was able to win the final stage and take time bonuses at the intermediate sprints.<ref name=cyclingnews-s5-terpstra>{{cite web|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Terpstra ready to fight for overall success at the Tour of Qatar|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/terpstra-ready-to-fight-for-overall-success-at-the-tour-of-qatar|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>

Following the stage, the race organisers announced that [[Lars Boom]] ({{ct|AST|2015|nolink=yes}}) had been disqualified from the race. His bike had developed a puncture about {{convert|20|km|0|abbr=on}} from the finish and he had attempted to regain contact with the peloton by chasing in the slipstream of his team car.<ref>{{cite web|title=News shorts: Merckx backs Contador's Giro-Tour double|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/news-shorts-merckx-backs-contadors-giro-tour-double|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>

